@Article{zion2012use,
  Title                    = {The use of computer vision technologies in aquaculture--a review},
  Author                   = {Zion, Boaz},
  Journal                  = {Computers and electronics in agriculture},
  Year                     = {2012},
  Pages                    = {125--132},
  Volume                   = {88},

  Abstract                 = {Computer vision technology is a sophisticated inspection technology that is in common use in various
industries. However, it is not as widely used in aquaculture. Application of computer vision technologies
in aquaculture, the scope of the present review, is very challenging. The inspected subjects are sensitive,
easily stressed and free to move in an environment in which lighting, visibility and stability are generally
not controllable, and the sensors must operate underwater or in a wet environment. The review describes
the state of the art and the evolution of computer vision in aquaculture, at all stages of production, from
hatcheries to harvest. The review is organized according to inspection tasks that are common to almost
all production systems: counting, size measurement and mass estimation, gender detection and quality
inspection, species and stock identification, and monitoring of welfare and behavior. The objective of the
review is to highlight areas of research and development in the field of computer vision which have made
some progress, but have not matured into a useful tool. There are many potential applications for this
technology in aquaculture which could be useful for improving product quality or production efficiency.
There have been quite a few initiatives in this direction, and a tight collaboration between engineers, fish
physiologists and ethologists could contribute to the search for, and development of solutions for the
benefit of aquaculture.},
  Owner                    = {cl15753},
  Publisher                = {Elsevier},
  Review                   = {Summary

Computer vision technologies are being used for inspection tasks in many industries with great success, however, these technologies are not widely used in aquaculture. This is mainly due to the difficulties involved in handling the inspection subjects (the fish), who are very sensitive, stress prone and have a great deal of movement freedom. The sensing technology also has to overcome a challenging environment, where light, visibility and stability are not always controllable and are often far from ideal. This review highlights some advances in the field of computer vision that may prove useful tools for aquaculture, and the author has separated these between five key identification tasks:
Counting.
Size measurement and mass estimation.
Gender identification and quality assessment.
Species and stock identification.
Welfare monitoring.

A recurring problem identified with many of these inspection tasks is to inspect the fish in situ and alive. For different tasks, the author suggests two approaches to this; the first is that there should be more of a focus on advancing underwater stereo imaging of live fish. The other is to change how the fish are handled so as to present them better for image processing, for example, a narrow channel system where the environment could be better controlled.

Comments

This review paper was very well structured, delivering its message in a clear and concise manner. It gives a good introduction to how computer vision can help in inspection tasks in agriculture, but only those which involve the fish directly. However, in the main body of the review it was hard to tell how different methods compared, or actually what quantified a good result or the time saving compared to the labour intensive methods.},
  Timestamp                = {2016.02.18}
}

